\subsection{Simplicial Homology}
Let us fix a field $k$. In the following, by vector space we intend $k-$vector space. 
Given a simplicial complex $X$ of dimension $d$, for any $n$ such that $0\leq n \leq d$ consider the vector space ${\mathrm{C}}_n:={\mathrm{C}}_n(X)$ of all the linear combinations of $n$-faces of $X$ with coefficients in $k$. Elements in ${\mathrm{C}}_n$ are called $n$\textit{-chains}.\\

The \textit{boundary} operators are the linear maps sending a $n$-face to the alternate sum of its $(n-1)$-faces, i.e.,
\begin{eqnarray*}
\partial_n: {\mathrm{C}}_n & \longrightarrow & {\mathrm{C}}_{n-1}\\
\text{[}p_{0},\ldots, p_{n}\text{]} & \rightarrow & \sum_{j=0}^n(-1)^i\text{[}p_{0}, \ldots, p_{{j-1}}, p_{{j+1}},\ldots, p_{n}\text{]}.\\
\end{eqnarray*}
They share the property $\partial_{n-1}\circ\partial_n=0$. The subspace $\ker\partial_n$ of ${\mathrm{C}}_n$ is called the vector space of $n$-\textit{cycles} and denoted by ${\mathrm{Z}}_n:={\mathrm{Z}}_n(X)$, with by convention ${\mathrm{Z}}_0 = \emptyset$.
The subspace  $\mathrm{Im}\,\partial_{n+1}$ of ${\mathrm{C}}_n$, is called the vector space of $n$-\textit{boundaries} and denoted by ${\mathrm{B}}_n:={\mathrm{B}}_n(X)$, with by convention ${\mathrm{B}}_d = \emptyset$. The property $\partial_{n-1}\circ\partial_n=0$ is then equivalent to ${\mathrm{B}}_n\subseteq {\mathrm{Z}}_n$ for all $n$.
\begin{definition}
For $0 \leqslant n \leqslant d$, the $n-$th simplicial homology space of $X$, with coefficients in $k$, is the vector space ${\mathrm{H}}_n:={\mathrm{H}}_n(X):={\mathrm{Z}}_n/{\mathrm{B}}_n$.
We denote by $\beta_n:=\beta_n(X)$ the dimension of ${\mathrm{H}}_n$ which is usually called the $n$-th Betti number of $X$. 
\end{definition}
Let us see two examples.
First, let us consider the simplicial complex $X$ consisting of a triangle $[p_{1}p_{2}p_{3}]$ and all its edges and vertices (i.e., $X=\{[p_1p_2p_3],[p_1p_2],[p_1p_3],[p_2p_3],[p_1],[p_2],[p_3]\}$). The boundary of the 2-simplex $[p_{1}p_{2}p_{3}]$ is
